[EEE virus transmission continues to be active in Massachusetts this year (2020). As noted earlier, the 1st human case of EEE appeared about 3 weeks after the virus was found in mosquitoes for the 1st time this year (2020). There are now 2 human cases in Plymouth county. There is a human case in Hampden county, as well. Last year (2019) was an unusually active year for EEE virus transmission in the eastern USA, with cases in humans and horses, including in Massachusetts. As mentioned in many previous ProMED-mail posts, horse owners in the eastern and upper midwestern USA states should vaccinate their animals now if they have not done so already. There is no commercially available vaccine for humans, so avoidance of mosquito bites is the only preventive measure to take.

Additional information on EEE is available on the CDC website at https://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis/. - Mod.TY

